Berry aka Yarn (modern) is a package manager split into various packages.
Its novel architecture allows to do things currently impossible.

Yarn supports plugins;
adding a plugin is as simple as adding it into your repository.

Yarn supports Node by default
but isn't limited to it - plugins can add support for other languages.

Yarn supports workspaces natively,
and its CLI takes advantage of that.

Yarn uses a bash-like portable shell
to make package scripts portable across Windows, Linux, and macOS.

Yarn is first and foremost a Node API
that can be used programmatically (via @yarnpkg/core).

Yarn is written in TypeScript and is fully type-checked.
